<font color="#FF0000">MEDALS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 12 17:50:40 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
We don't have to apologize for anything.<br><br>
I attended  ceremonies in DC over Veteran's Day. I met a fellow at the Americal tent who wore a Silver Star ribbon. I mentioned to him that I had one. He immediately said, &quot;Why arent't you wearing it?&quot; Until recently, I had gone almost 30 years afraid to talk of my achievement. <br><br>
I stammered out a response like I was embarrassed and didn't want to &quot;show anyone up&quot;. He told me that the only way that other guys would feel proud of their service in Vietnam was if the guys who won medals were proud to display them. I am proud of my service there.<br><br>
Recently, I bought a jungle fatigue shirt - non camoflage, Army Issue. Am looking for subdued CIB and E5 stripes. I already have the Americal patch, and have a line on a 198th patch. I will proudly wear it next Veteran's Day in DC when I will attend those ceremonies.<br><br>
Having said this, caution should be observed because open display of medals can mean that a response is implicit. There may be no response (don't get your feelings hurt), or there may be a negative responses like those above messages which are anonymously posted.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


